Africa
---
[4] DRC
Date: Wed 25 Sep 2019
Source: The Telegraph [abridged, edited]
https://www.telegraph.co.uk/global-health/science-and-disease/measles-kills-3600-children-drc-third-emergency-vaccine-drive/


Almost a million children will be vaccinated against measles in the Democratic Republic of Congo (DRC), in a bid to stem the world's largest outbreak of this deadly disease.

The devastating childhood illness has killed 3667 children and infected close to 184 000 people already this year [2019] in the DRC -- a country that is also battling to control Ebola.

On Wednesday [25 Sep 2019], the government initiated the 3rd mass vaccination campaign -- in collaboration with the World Health Organization (WHO) , Medecins Sans Frontieres (MSF) and Unicef -- in an effort to bring the enormous measles outbreak to a close.

The epidemic this year [2019] in the DRC is the country's worst for more than a decade and is spreading like wildfire; it is the fastest-growing measles outbreak worldwide.

"Measles is everywhere -- every province of the country has cases," Dr. Karel Janssens, head of mission for MSF in the DRC, told The Telegraph from Kinshasa. "This is a very lethal epidemic."

The latest vaccination campaign, which will run for 9 days, will target close to 825 000 children under 5 years of age in 24 of the country's 26 provinces. The WHO says this will make the total number of children vaccinated through emergency campaigns to 4.1 million.

This year [2019] has seen measles outbreaks sweeping the globe, as a combination of growing anti-vax sentiment and a lack of access to crucial health care has left hundreds of thousands of people vulnerable to one of the world's most contagious viruses.

Africa alone has seen a 900% increase in infections compared with 2018.

But low vaccination rates in the DRC -- which is home to 81 million people, 40% of whom are under the age of 14 -- are not due to scepticism.

"The DRC is experiencing a dire situation because too many children were missed by routine immunisation," said Dr. Deo Nshimirimana, the WHO representative in the DRC.

And so a highly contagious disease such as measles pops up again and just ravishes through a population with barely any herd immunity," he said. "This epidemic is not new; it's high time that more actors were involved and more resources went into this."

The WHO has established a measles response advocacy committee to mobilise partners and donors in a joint effort to control the outbreak, and the United Nations Humanitarian Pooled Fund has given USD 2.5 million to the government's emergency campaign.

The DRC's Ministry of Health has also provided USD 843 000 to purchase vaccines.

But even with the scale-up of vaccination efforts -- which are not being used to prevent measles moving into new regions, but to try and stem the growing death toll -- it is unlikely that the epidemic will end soon.

"I'm afraid that this epidemic will continue," said Mr. Janssens. "And as much as it is important to respond now to the current epidemic, of course it's key to start thinking beyond this about how to avoid [a situation in which] every couple of years we end up with such a deadly epidemic."

[Byline: Sarah Newey]

